      {
        "user": "How does \"transformer (architecture)\" differ from MoE (Mixture of Experts)?",
        "assistant": "A **Transformer** and a **Mixture of Experts (MoE)** are different kinds of ideas.\n\n## Short version\n\nA **Transformer** is a neural network **architecture** based on self-attention for processing sequences.\n\nAn **MoE** is a **scaling technique** where different parts of a model, called “experts,” handle different inputs.\n\nIn practice, many modern MoE models are still **Transformers** — they are Transformers with some layers replaced or augmented by Mixture-of-Experts layers.\n\n---\n\n## 1. What each one is\n\n### Transformer\n\nA Transformer defines how information flows through a sequence.\n\nIts main components are:\n\n- token embeddings\n- positional information\n- self-attention\n- feed-forward layers\n- residual connections\n- layer normalization\n\nA simplified Transformer block looks like:\n\n```text\nInput\n ↓\nSelf-attention\n ↓\nFeed-forward network\n ↓\nOutput\n```\n\nThe key idea is that tokens can attend to other tokens using **self-attention**.\n\n---\n\n### Mixture of Experts\n\nAn MoE layer contains multiple separate neural networks called **experts**.\n\nA small network called a **router** or **gating network** decides which expert, or experts, should process each token.\n\nSimplified:\n\n```text\nToken\n ↓\nRouter\n ↓\nExpert 3 and Expert 7\n ↓\nOutput\n```\n\nInstead of every token going through the same feed-forward network, different tokens may go through different experts.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Architecture vs component\n\nA Transformer is a full architecture.\n\nMoE is usually a component inside an architecture.\n\nFor example, a normal Transformer block might have:\n\n```text\nSelf-attention\n ↓\nFeed-forward network\n```\n\nAn MoE Transformer block might have:\n\n```text\nSelf-attention\n ↓\nMixture-of-Experts feed-forward layer\n```\n\nSo MoE often replaces the standard dense feed-forward network inside some Transformer layers.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Dense model vs sparse model\n\n### Standard Transformer\n\nIn a regular dense Transformer, every token uses the same model parameters.\n\nIf the model has 10 billion parameters, a token may use most or all relevant parameters during computation.\n\n```text\nEvery token → same layers → same parameter set\n```\n\n### MoE Transformer\n\nIn an MoE model, the total model may have many more parameters, but each token only activates a small subset of them.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nTotal experts: 64\nExperts used per token: 2\n```\n\nSo the model may have a very large parameter count, but the computation per token is much smaller than using all experts.\n\nThis is called **sparse activation**.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Main purpose\n\n### Transformer\n\nThe purpose of the Transformer architecture is to model relationships in data, especially sequences.\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> How should tokens communicate with each other?\n\nThe answer is:\n\n> Through self-attention and feed-forward transformations.\n\n---\n\n### MoE\n\nThe purpose of MoE is to increase model capacity efficiently.\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> How can we make the model much larger without making every token use the entire model?\n\nThe answer is:\n\n> Use a router to send each token to only a few specialized experts.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Attention vs routing\n\n### Transformer self-attention\n\nSelf-attention decides which **tokens** should interact with which other tokens.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"it\" attends to \"dog\"\n```\n\nThis helps the model understand relationships inside the sequence.\n\n---\n\n### MoE routing\n\nMoE routing decides which **expert networks** should process a token.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nmath token → math-like expert\ncode token → code-like expert\nFrench token → multilingual expert\n```\n\nThough in practice, experts are not always so cleanly interpretable.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Typical Transformer block vs MoE Transformer block\n\n### Dense Transformer block\n\n```text\nInput tokens\n ↓\nSelf-attention\n ↓\nFeed-forward network\n ↓\nOutput tokens\n```\n\n### MoE Transformer block\n\n```text\nInput tokens\n ↓\nSelf-attention\n ↓\nRouter\n ↓\nSelected experts\n ↓\nCombine expert outputs\n ↓\nOutput tokens\n```\n\nThe attention part may remain mostly the same. The major change is usually in the feed-forward part.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Parameter count vs compute cost\n\nMoE models can have a huge number of total parameters, but only use some of them for each token.\n\nFor example, imagine an MoE model with:\n\n```text\n8 experts\n2 experts used per token\n```\n\nEach token only activates 2 out of 8 experts.\n\nSo compared with a dense model, MoE can increase total capacity without increasing compute proportionally.\n\nThis is one reason MoE is attractive for large language models.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Tradeoffs\n\nMoE has benefits, but it also adds complexity.\n\n### Benefits of MoE\n\n- More parameters without proportional compute increase\n- Potential specialization among experts\n- Efficient scaling\n- Strong performance for large models\n\n### Challenges of MoE\n\n- Routing can be unstable\n- Load balancing is difficult\n- Some experts may be overused while others are underused\n- Training and serving are more complex\n- Communication overhead can be high across GPUs\n\n---\n\n## 9. Comparison table\n\n| Feature | Transformer | MoE |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | Neural network architecture | Model scaling technique/component |\n| Main idea | Self-attention between tokens | Route tokens to selected experts |\n| Core mechanism | Attention | Gating/routing |\n| Used for | Sequence modeling, language, vision, audio | Increasing capacity efficiently |\n| Can stand alone? | Yes | Usually part of a larger architecture |\n| Common combination | Transformer model | MoE inside Transformer layers |\n| Computation style | Usually dense | Usually sparse |\n| Example models | GPT-style models, BERT, T5, ViT | Switch Transformer, Mixtral-style models, GShard-style models |\n\n---\n\n## In short\n\nA **Transformer** is the overall architecture that uses **self-attention** to process tokens.\n\nAn **MoE** is a technique that adds multiple specialized **expert networks** and uses a **router** to choose which experts handle each token.\n\nSo they are not direct alternatives in the same way as Transformer vs RNN or Transformer vs CNN. Instead, MoE is often used **inside Transformers** to make them larger and more compute-efficient.",
